  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What are mushroom coffee gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Mushroom coffee gummies combine functional mushroom extracts (lion\'s mane for focus, cordyceps for energy, chaga for immune support) with a small amount of natural caffeine — typically 25-50mg, roughly half a cup of coffee. The goal is to provide the alertness and focus of coffee without the jitters, crash, and anxiety that higher caffeine doses can cause. The functional mushrooms add cognitive, energetic, and immune-supporting benefits that regular coffee lacks. This category has grown 340% since 2023, driven by consumers seeking "cleaner" energy that supports rather than depletes the nervous system.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much caffeine do mushroom coffee gummies contain?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Most mushroom coffee gummies contain 25-50mg of caffeine per serving — approximately one-quarter to one-half the caffeine in a standard cup of coffee (95mg). Some products are completely caffeine-free, relying solely on cordyceps and lion\'s mane for natural energy and focus. The reduced caffeine is intentional: functional mushrooms like cordyceps enhance cellular energy production through ATP pathway support (not CNS stimulation), while lion\'s mane supports nerve growth factor (NGF) for sustained cognitive function. The small caffeine dose provides initial alertness while the mushrooms sustain focus and energy without the crash.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Which mushrooms are used in mushroom coffee gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The most common functional mushrooms in coffee alternatives are: Lion\'s mane (Hericium erinaceus) — supports cognitive function by stimulating nerve growth factor (NGF) production; Cordyceps (Cordyceps militaris) — enhances cellular energy by supporting ATP production and oxygen utilization; Chaga (Inonotus obliquus) — provides powerful antioxidant support with one of the highest ORAC scores of any food; Reishi (Ganoderma lucidum) — calms the nervous system and supports immune function; and Turkey tail (Trametes versicolor) — supports gut health and immune function. Most products use a combination of 2-4 of these mushrooms.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Do mushroom coffee gummies actually improve focus?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The evidence is strongest for lion\'s mane. A 2009 double-blind RCT in Phytotherapy Research gave adults 3g of lion\'s mane daily for 16 weeks and found significant improvements in cognitive function scores compared to placebo. Lion\'s mane contains hericenones and erinacines — compounds that stimulate nerve growth factor (NGF), a protein essential for the growth, maintenance, and survival of neurons. For cordyceps, a 2010 study in the Journal of Alternative and Complementary Medicine found that Cordyceps militaris improved exercise tolerance and VO2 max. The combination of lion\'s mane (cognitive) and cordyceps (physical energy) plus modest caffeine creates a multi-pathway focus and energy support system.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Are mushroom coffee gummies safe?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Functional mushroom supplements have been used in traditional Chinese and Japanese medicine for centuries and have a strong safety profile. Modern clinical trials of lion\'s mane, cordyceps, chaga, and reishi have reported no serious adverse effects at standard supplemental doses. However, individuals with mushroom allergies should avoid these products. People taking blood thinners should use caution with reishi (which has antiplatelet effects). Individuals with autoimmune conditions should consult their physician, as some mushrooms stimulate immune function. Pregnant and nursing women should consult their healthcare provider before taking functional mushroom supplements.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the difference between fruiting body and mycelium extracts?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The fruiting body is the above-ground mushroom structure (the cap and stem you would recognize as a mushroom). Mycelium is the underground root-like network. Fruiting body extracts contain higher concentrations of beta-glucans, terpenoids, and other bioactive compounds — the molecules responsible for most studied health benefits. Mycelium grown on grain substrates often contains significant starch filler from the grain, diluting the active mushroom compounds. Products labeled "fruiting body extract" are generally considered superior. Look for beta-glucan content (ideally more than 20%) as a quality indicator.' } },
